06789nam a22006735i 9780822390664DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20082008ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223906647 a10.1515/97808223906642doi  a(DE-B1597)554288  a(OCoLC)1136176262  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aHIS0240002bisacsh04a980.03300aIn from the Cold :bLatin America's New Encounter with the Cold War /cGilbert M. Joseph, Emily S. Rosenberg, Daniela Spenser. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (450 p.) :b17 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerican encounters/global interactions00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tI. New Approaches, Debates, and Sources -- tWhat We Now Know and Should Know: Bringing Latin America More Meaningfully into Cold War Studies -- tRecovering the Memory of the Cold War: Forensic History and Latin America -- tII. Latin America between the Superpowers: International Realpolitik, the Ideology of the State, and the ''Latin Americanization'' of the Conflict -- tThe Caribbean Crisis: Catalyst for Soviet Projection in Latin America -- tThe View from Havana: Lessons from Cuba's African Journey, 1959-1976 -- tTransnationalizing the Dirty War: Argentina in Central America -- tIII. Everyday Contests over Culture and Representation in the Latin American Cold War -- tProducing the Cold War in Mexico: The Public Limits of Covert Communications -- t¡Cuba sí, Yanquis no! The Sacking of the Instituto Cultural México- Norteamericano in Morelia, Michoacán, 1961 -- tMiracle on Ice: Industrial Workers and the Promise of Americanization in Cold War Mexico -- tChicano Cold Warriors: César Chávez, Mexican American Politics, and California Farmworkers -- tBirth Control Pills and Molotov Cocktails: Reading Sex and Revolution in 1968 Brazil -- tRural Markets, Revolutionary Souls, and Rebellious Women in Cold War Guatemala -- tIV. Final Reflections -- tStanding Conventional Cold War History on Its Head Daniela Spenser -- tSelective Bibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOver the last decade, studies of the Cold War have mushroomed globally. Unfortunately, work on Latin America has not been well represented in either theoretical or empirical discussions of the broader conflict. With some notable exceptions, studies have proceeded in rather conventional channels, focusing on U.S. policy objectives and high-profile leaders (Fidel Castro) and events (the Cuban Missile Crisis) and drawing largely on U.S. government sources. Moreover, only rarely have U.S. foreign relations scholars engaged productively with Latin American historians who analyze how the international conflict transformed the region's political, social, and cultural life. Representing a collaboration among eleven North American, Latin American, and European historians, anthropologists, and political scientists, this volume attempts to facilitate such a cross-fertilization. In the process, In From the Cold shifts the focus of attention away from the bipolar conflict, the preoccupation of much of the so-called "new Cold War history," in order to showcase research, discussion, and an array of new archival and oral sources centering on the grassroots, where conflicts actually brewed.The collection's contributors examine international and everyday contests over political power and cultural representation, focusing on communities and groups above and underground, on state houses and diplomatic board rooms manned by Latin American and international governing elites, on the relations among states regionally, and, less frequently, on the dynamics between the two great superpowers themselves. In addition to charting new directions for research on the Latin American Cold War, In From the Cold seeks to contribute more generally to an understanding of the conflict in the global south.Contributors. Ariel C. Armony, Steven J. Bachelor, Thomas S. Blanton, Seth Fein, Piero Gleijeses, Gilbert M. Joseph, Victoria Langland, Carlota McAllister, Stephen Pitti, Daniela Spenser, Eric Zolov  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 7aHISTORY / Latin America / General.2bisacsh1 aArmony, Ariel C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcAllister, Carlota, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSpenser, Daniela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZolov, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoseph, Gilbert M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoseph, Gilbert M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGleijeses, Piero, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosenberg, Emily S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFein, Seth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSpenser, Daniela, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPitti, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBachelor, Steven J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlanton, Thomas S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLangland, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822390664zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822390664423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822390664.jpg  a978-3-11-071183